07288nam a22013575i 9783839450185DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97838394501857 a10.1515/97838394501852doi  a(DE-B1597)537375  a(OCoLC)1202624815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04817u818pa307.1216qDE-101223/ger00aUrban Resilience in a Global Context :bActors, Narratives, and Temporalities /ced. by Dorothee Brantz, Avi Sharma. 1aBielefeld : btranscript Verlag, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUrban Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tI). Introduction -- tContesting Resilience -- tII). Ecologies of Resilience -- tA Historical Perspective on Resilient Urbanism -- tNorth of the Arctic Circle -- tGrowing Resilient Cities -- tBefore 'Resilience' -- tIII). Infrastructures of Resilience -- tNo Easy Solutions -- tBuilding Resilience through Commercial Relations -- tEnhancing Urban Resilience After the 1995 Kobe Earthquake -- tTransportation as a Resilience Enhancing Tool -- tIV). Epilogue -- tUrban Resilience Has a History - And a Future -- tAuthor Bios0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aUrban Resilience is seen by many as a tool to mitigate harm in times of extreme social, political, financial, and environmental stress. Despite its widespread usage, however, resilience is used in different ways by policy makers, activists, academics, and practitioners. Some see it as a key to unlocking a more stable and secure urban future in times of extreme global insecurity; for others, it is a neoliberal technology that marginalizes the voices of already marginal peoples. This volume moves beyond praise and critique by focusing on the actors, agendas, and narratives that define urban resilience in a global context. By exploring the past, present, and future of urban resilience, this volume unlocks the potential of this concept to build more sustainable, inclusive, and secure cities in the 21st century.  afunded by TU Berlin  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aBelgium. 4aCity. 4aClimate Change. 4aColombia. 4aFrance. 4aGermany. 4aGlobalization. 4aInfrastructure. 4aInternational Development. 4aJapan. 4aMexico. 4aNature. 4aNeoliberalism. 4aNew Zealand. 4aPolitical Ecology. 4aResource Management. 4aRight To the City. 4aSociology. 4aSustainability. 4aSustainable Development. 4aUrban History. 4aUrban Nature. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aBelgium.  aCity.  aClimate Change.  aColombia.  aFrance.  aGermany.  aGlobalization.  aInfrastructure.  aInternational Development.  aJapan.  aMexico.  aNature.  aNeoliberalism.  aNew Zealand.  aPolitical Ecology.  aResource Management.  aRight To the City.  aSociology.  aSustainability.  aSustainable Development.  aUrban History.  aUrban Nature.  aUrban Studies.1 aBrantz, Dorothee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrantz, Dorothee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDanneels, Koenraad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Block, Greet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunkel, Sönke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiedtke, Florian Hendrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, Marcela, econtributo